Also. What happened to puzzlemucker?  The guy with the penguin profile pick. He was a stalwart.

@Vislander
Thanks  for reporting in, V. 
I don't understand this. Is he saying he's unable to post comments?! That's very strange. Is it the emus? Or their human controllers? Or someone at Mr Connell's end? Sounds like a Gothic novel in real life. I sure hope he's OK.

@Mo

Doner is used in the UK as well but normally in the NYT crossword such things are kebab or kabob. 

I got LIED crossing with DONER pretty early, but I was suspicious of both because I hadn’t seen it before.

@Mo

In the US, the term DONER kebab is largely unknown; we have the Greek equivalent, the gyro, which is nearly the same thing, and the middle eastern shawarma, which is minimally different. The Turks were late to the game, apparently, in the US. 

(DONER, shawarma and gyro all refer, in Turkish, Arabic and Greek respectively, to turning, in reference to the rotisserie used.)

@Steve L

Those who think that a DONER is nearly the same thing as a Gyro haven't had a really good DONER.

I had a really good DONER last time I was in Berlin, and I still dream about it.

@Barry Ancona

I've had some good Gyros, but I'm always up to try a new place.
Any recommendations?

@SP

Agreed. Great puzzle. Very solvable for us non US folk as well. I’ve never heard of COLORWARS, but using tugofWARS at first got me there in the end. I liked DOMED for ‘rounded up’. 

Slight concern I cheated a bit as OUTINLA is visible from my seat along with my other Chilli Pepper CDs, but I’m going to assume the crossword gods planned that serendipity.

