@Don H
As others have commented, I love the wrong but oh-so-plausible clue. Mine this time was 10A: FLAT, GRAY, or DEAD? Note that all have A in the 3rd spot; so annoying because I got ARABIAN and it did not help.

Well-clued!

@Lizzie Boredom
I kept wracking my brain, trying to remember "What is that thing called that's on the menu at Supergeil, in Corktown?"

(Is theirs good? I have little to compare it to, although I've also eaten Döner at a Turkish restaurant in Windsor.)

@C
at least one solver was misdirected to "scythe".
and while I was passing familiar with the CELESTA (or CELESTe) I had never thought about the root word.

@Barry Ancona

I’m not surprised that newer solvers would describe today’s puzzle as hard, but I’ve seen a few “proper Saturday” comments from folks who seem less new…though I guess that may just be a reflection of how far the difficulty calibration has moved these last few years.

Incidentally, regarding the newer solvers, it seems like this puzzle is kind of a sweet spot for many of them — if we got what I’d call a proper Saturday, there would be a chorus of newbies *criticizing* the puzzle, and insisting that they are objecting not to the puzzle’s difficulty, but an excess of obscure trivia, unfair clues, etc.

@Anonymous
57:25, no look-ups!
<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tAMz9WqkNBA&list=RDtAMz9WqkNBA&start_radio=1" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tAMz9WqkNBA&list=RDtAMz9WqkNBA&start_radio=1</a>

@Anonymous
I worked through it all. Upper third and middle right we’re ok, had to reveal a lot of words in the bottom third and middle left. Some of the bottom third felt like letter salad to fit the four spanners. Obscure trivia just to get it to hang together.
And there are three or four answers I just don’t understand even though I filled them in, which is my problem, so maybe they are awesome clues or maybe they are not.

@Francis

If you have to ask…

J/K. I’m actually not a long-time solver myself. I just tend to group myself into that category as a matter of convenience/concision, as this forum can generally be partitioned into people who tend to find recent puzzles much easier than they’d prefer (“old-timers”) and those who find the current level of challenge adequate (“newer solvers”).

